msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:32
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"-e # edit crontab scheduled tasks\n"
"the -l # View crontab task\n"
"-r # delete all the current user's crontab tasks\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use of cronie"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "To allow different users to execute different commands (or scripts) at different times, they can be written into this file. However, usually we are more accustomed to using `crontab -e`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:42
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shell > cat /etc/crontab\n"
"SHELL=/bin/bash\n"
"PATH=/sbin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin\n"
"MAILTO=root\n"
"# For details see man 4 crontabs\n"
"# Example of job definition:\n"
"# .---------------- minute (0-59)\n"
"# | .------------- hour (0-23)\n"
"# | | .---------- day of month (1-31)\n"
"# | | | .------- month (1-12) OR jan,feb,mar,apr ...\n"
"# | | | | .---- day of week (0-6) (Sunday=0 or 7) OR sun,mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat\n"
"# | | | | |\n"
"# * * * * * user-name command to be executed\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:65
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"|Parameter|Meaning|Value Range|\n"
"|---|---|---|\n"
"|The 1st\\*|The first minute of the hour|0-59|\n"
"|The 2nd\\*|Hour of the day|0-23|\n"
"|The 3rd\\*|Day of the month|1-31|\n"
"|The 4th\\*|The month of the year|1-12|\n"
"|The 5th\\*|Day of the week|0-7 (0 and 7 both indicate Sunday)|\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the example that follows, assuming you are performing this operation as the root user, type the following: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "`crontab -e` which will bring up the timed tasks of the root user. If you use `vi` as the default system editor, press <kbd>i</kbd> key to enter the insert mode. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"#\" means this is a line of comment.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Nightly 10:00 backup system\n"
"00 22 *  *  * /usr/local/sbin/backup\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once the above has been entered (again assuming `vi` is the system editor), press <kbd>ESC</kbd> to exit insert mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "Save and exit your file with <kbd>SHIFT</kbd>+<kbd>:</kbd>+<kbd>wq!</kbd> (displayed at the bottom of the editor).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now the script will run every night at 22:00. This is a simplistic example. Things can become more complicated if you need something more elaborate.\n"
msgstr ""

