#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "Complex Options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:88
#, no-wrap
msgid "The content discussed so far are simplistic options, but what about more complex timed tasks?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Suppose you want to run every 10 minutes backup script (may be impractical, however, it is only an example!) Throughout the day. To this end, the following will be written:\n"
"* /10 *  *  *  * /usr/local/sbin/backup\n"
"#What if you only want to run a backup every 10 minutes on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday? :\n"
"* /10 *  *  * 1,3,5 /usr/local/sbin/backup\n"
"# In addition to Saturdays and Sundays, once every 10 minutes, every day, how to back up?\n"
"* /10 *  *  * 1-5 /usr/local/sbin/backup\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:104
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"|Special Symbols|Meaning|\n"
"|---|---|\n"
"|* | represents any time. For example, the first * means any minute, and the second * means any hour |\n"
"|, | stands for discontinuous time, such as \"0 8,12,16 * * * \", which means that the command will run once every day at 8:00, 12:00, and 16:00 |\n"
"|- | represents a continuous time range, such as \"0 5 * * 1-6 \", which means that a command will run at five o'clock in the morning every day from Monday to Saturday |\n"
"|*/n | Represents how often the interval will run, such as \"*/10 * * * *\" means that it  every 10 minutes |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The smallest time unit that cronie can recognize is 1 minute; when using, for example, `30 4 1,15 * 5 command` , it will cause the command to run on the 1st and 15th of each month and 4:30 in the morning of every Friday ; The output information of some scripts or commands will prevent the execution of timed tasks, and output redirection is required, such as this- `*/10 * * * * /usr/local/sbin/backup &> /dev/null`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:109
#, no-wrap
msgid "Q and A"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cronie.md:120
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. /etc/crontab and `crontab -e` , is there any difference between the two methods?\n"
" `crontab -e` does not need to specify a user (the currently logged-in user is used by default), while /etc/crontab needs to specify a user.\n"
"2. What should you do if the specified command or script is not run correctly?\n"
"Check the /var/log/cron* file, use `journalctl -u crond.service` to check the information about the daemon process, whether the script has x permission, etc., for troubleshooting.\n"
"3. In addition to cronie, what cron variants are there?\n"
"[ dcron ](http://www.jimpryor.net/linux/dcron.html), the latest version is 4.5 (2011-50-01).\n"
"[ fcron ](http://fcron.free.fr/), the latest version is 3.3.0 (dev, 2016-08-14).\n"
"[ bcron ](http://untroubled.org/bcron/), the latest version is 0.11 (2015-08-12).\n"
"[ cronsun ](https://github.com/shunfei/cronsun), the latest version 0.3.5 (2018-11-20).\n"
msgstr ""

